mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: A template common in many games is that leveling up gives an automatic increase in the character's base stats such as HP, mana or stamina
mxTextCell.prevLabel: A template common in many games is that leveling up gives an automatic increase in the character's base stats such as HP, mana or stamina

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: Leveling up in almost all MOBA games gives the player one skill point that can be spent on one of three abilities, and an ultimate that can be invested in at certain levels only. Two points cannot be invested in the same ability consecutively at the beginning of the game.
mxTextCell.prevLabel: Leveling up in almost all MOBA games gives the player one skill point that can be spent on one of three abilities, and an ultimate that can be invested in at certain levels only. Two points cannot be invested in the same ability consecutively at the beginning of the game.

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: Some games give the player skill points that can be invested in certain skill trees, meaning that in order to unlock the second skill of a tree you must first unlock its first skill. An example of such a game is Dragon Age: Origins
mxTextCell.prevLabel: Some games give the player skill points that can be invested in certain skill trees, meaning that in order to unlock the second skill of a tree you must first unlock its first skill. An example of such a game is Dragon Age: Origins

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: A variation of the skill tree example is a tree where each skill is upgradeable so more points can be invested in it. Usually this means that subsequent skills are unlocked when the user spends a certain amount of points in a skill tree. An example of such a game is The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: Some games don't automatically level the character up when the required XP is reached. Instead the XP is stored and the character has a specific place or time when he can use that XP to level up. This can give the player multiple level ups in one sitting. An example of such a game is Dark Souls

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: NFS Heat uses a system where the player earns reputation and steadily increases his Heat level by completing races and running from cops. When the player returns to the garage for the night all of the earned reputation is multiplied by the Heat level to give the player the total experience for the night.
mxTextCell.prevLabel: NFS Heat uses a system where the player earns reputation and steadily increases his Heat level by completing races and running from cops. When the player returns to the garage for the night all of the earned reputation is multiplied by the Heat level to give the player the total experience for the night.

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: Another variation of this model is Final Fantasy XV's model, where the player stores XP throughout the day (or multiple days) and then decides to rest. All of the experience is then multiplied by an amount correspondent to the place where the player slept (more expensive locations give a bigger experience boost). Leveling up gives the player AP, which he can spend on skills.

mxTextCell.title: Text
mxTextCell.label: Other games use a model where the player does not have a single XP bar, instead each specific skill has its own bar and progress and levels up individually (generally through the usage of that skill). Leveling up a skill gives some progress towards a general level up and a general level up gives the player general bonuses (increased stats for instance). Such a model can be seen in The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim.
